WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.800
Now, data from the Labor Department

00:00:01.800 --> 00:00:04.170
shows the great resignation is actually

00:00:04.170 --> 00:00:06.420
improving in most US states.

00:00:06.420 --> 00:00:11.220
4.3 million Americans quit their jobs in December of 2021.

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:14.640
And that is down from a record high of 4 and 1/2 million

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:15.970
in November.

00:00:15.970 --> 00:00:18.810
However, the report also shows the great resignation

00:00:18.810 --> 00:00:21.000
worsened in eight states.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.070
Some experts believe many people are still

00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:25.800
contemplating other employment options, especially

00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:29.230
those that were not available prior to the pandemic.

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:31.950
For more on that, I want to bring in Karin Kimbrough.

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:34.620
She's the chief economist at LinkedIn.

00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:36.690
So Karin, in addition to people who

00:00:36.690 --> 00:00:38.280
quit their jobs during the pandemic,

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:39.910
there are those who have chosen to work

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:42.780
remotely from other locations that they find more desirable.

00:00:42.780 --> 00:00:45.960
How can companies convince these employees to start

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:48.270
coming back to the office?

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:48.870
Sure.

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.830
Well, there's a number of things that companies

00:00:50.830 --> 00:00:54.210
are starting to do to try to cast that wider net and lure

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:57.060
employees, potential employees, especially,

00:00:57.060 --> 00:00:58.440
back from the sidelines.

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:00.360
One of those things is they are definitely

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:04.770
starting to try to structure job applications that

00:01:04.770 --> 00:01:06.150
allow for career pauses.

00:01:06.150 --> 00:01:07.920
So we're seeing an increase in people

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.630
who are feeling quite comfortable saying,

00:01:09.630 --> 00:01:11.020
I took a pause in my career.

00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:14.100
I took six months off, a year off, and now I'm looking.

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:15.810
And employers are not necessarily

00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:19.800
penalizing job seekers for that anymore.

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:23.430
They're also allowing people to have a lot more flexibility

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:25.020
in terms of where they live.

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:28.650
They can work remotely, have hybrid, have flexible hours

00:01:28.650 --> 00:01:31.960
during their day or depending on which day they want to work.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:34.650
And then finally, we're also seeing that employers

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:37.050
are doing quite a lot to just make

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:39.780
the workplace more of a place that's charged,

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:43.260
that feels like you have a connection, a collaboration

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:44.590
with your colleagues.

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:47.660
So a place that might be fun to work at.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:50.240
Well, some experts believe that the best

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:51.950
way to keep employees happy going forward

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:55.670
is to offer some sort of remote work policy that would have

00:01:55.670 --> 00:01:57.320
hybrid or flexible options.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.000
What's your take on that?

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.230
Absolutely.

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:03.170
I can tell you the data do not lie.

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:07.070
Before the pandemic, we had maybe one in every 67 jobs

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:08.090
that was remote.

00:02:08.090 --> 00:02:09.560
Now it's one in six.

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:13.190
So we've had literally this abundance of jobs that

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:14.910
are remote on our platform.

00:02:14.910 --> 00:02:16.730
And that's not even accounting for the fact

00:02:16.730 --> 00:02:20.490
that we have far more jobs on our platform than ever before.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:22.580
In addition to that, nearly a third

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:26.480
of all the companies on LinkedIn are considering

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:29.750
offering some kind of remote or hybrid flexible work

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:30.680
arrangement.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:32.720
And so I think really what it is that people

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.160
don't miss their commute.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:37.530
They like the flexibility to be able to structure their day.

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:39.320
And I do think that when we look forward

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:41.450
into what does the future of work look like,

00:02:41.450 --> 00:02:45.140
it will definitely include a permanent place

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.400
for remote and hybrid work.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:49.050
It's very popular these days.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:51.440
So which industries right now currently

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:52.880
have the strongest hiring rates?

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:55.370
And what's contributing to that?

00:02:55.370 --> 00:02:57.200
Yeah, actually, I'm glad you mentioned that.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.730
The hiring rates have been really strong in January.

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:02.990
So despite some concern about the direction of the economy,

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:04.880
I can tell you from what we can see here

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:07.970
at LinkedIn in our data, in real time in the US,

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:09.720
the labor market is very strong.

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:12.770
We're seeing people very interested in coming back

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:13.890
from the sidelines to work.

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:16.070
And we're seeing employers very competitively

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:18.620
bidding for these workers.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:21.410
Some of the industries that are really top of mind

00:03:21.410 --> 00:03:25.100
are recreation and travel, software and IT,

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:26.720
and of course, transport logistics.

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:28.880
All that online shopping is creating

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:31.980
a lot of roles in transport and logistics.

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:34.140
Yeah, lots of jobs for truck drivers right now.

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:34.640
Indeed.

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:35.720
One more question for you.

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:38.420
As we prepare for the pandemic to become an endemic,

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:40.520
what are some employment and workplace

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:44.520
trends that we might start seeing in the coming year?

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:46.550
One of the things that we've keyed on

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:48.380
is this idea that employers are going

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:53.480
to be looking to structure their sort of job search

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:56.120
for candidates in terms of skills.

00:03:56.120 --> 00:04:00.560
So it won't be so much about necessarily just what

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:04.160
educational degree you have but also what skills can you bring.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:06.830
And they're going to be more flexible about letting

00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:09.950
people come from different sectors and transition in.

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:12.410
I mean, this great resignation that we're all talking about

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:13.850
is really a great reshuffle.

00:04:13.850 --> 00:04:16.970
It's a people quitting one job and moving to another.

00:04:16.970 --> 00:04:19.640
We're seeing a lot of that on our platform.

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:21.020
And people are leaving industries

00:04:21.020 --> 00:04:23.180
and moving into whole new ones.

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:26.210
We have seen a lot of people leaving, for example, education

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:30.650
and moving into customer service and project management

00:04:30.650 --> 00:04:32.610
because they require a lot of the same skills

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:33.630
if you think about it.

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:37.340
So what we're finding is that this transition happening

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:40.400
across America where people are being very open to moving

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:42.820
is something that's likely to continue.

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:44.690
And we're going to see this increase in labor

00:04:44.690 --> 00:04:46.860
mobility for quite some time.

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:49.190
And I think what it's going to mean for employers

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:53.330
is that they're going to have to find ways to retain the talent,

00:04:53.330 --> 00:04:56.270
make it attractive if it means paying up in wages,

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:59.270
making the workplace more enjoyable,

00:04:59.270 --> 00:05:04.480
or just offering better benefits in terms of flexibility.

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:06.450
It is an evolving workplace these days.

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:09.210
Sometimes, it seems like it'll never go back entirely

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:10.650
to the way that it used to be.

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:13.560
Karin Kimbrough, thank you very much for joining us.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:15.110
Thank you.